 | isbn = 978-0312047849}}\n* {{Cite book | author = Matthews, Marvyn | title = Education in the Soviet Union: Policies and Institutions since Stalin | publisher = [[Routledge]] | isbn = 978-0043701140 | year = 1983 | ref = CITEREFMatthews1983 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/libertarianseduc0000smit }}\n* {{cite book | author = [[Richard Sakwa|Sakwa, Richard]] | ref = CITEREFSakwa1990 | title = Soviet politics: an Introduction | location =  | publisher = [[Routledge]] | year = 1990 | isbn = 978-0415005067 | url = https://archive.org/details/sovietpoliticsin00sakw }}\n* {{cite book | author = [[Richard Sakwa|Sakwa, Richard]] |  ref = CITEREFSakwa1998 | title = Soviet politics in Perspective | location = | publisher = [[Routledge]] | year = 1998 | isbn = 978-0415071536}}\n* {{cite book | title = Soviet Politics: Continuity and Contradictions | year = 1988 | isbn = 978-0312007959 | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] | author = Smith, Gordon | ref = CITEREFSmith1988 | url = https://archive.org/details/sovietpoliticsco0000smit }}\n* {{ cite book | title = Soviet Politics: Continuity and Contradictions | url = https://archive.org/details/sovietpoliticsst00smit | url-access = registration | year = 1991 | isbn = 978-0333535769 | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] | author = Smith, Gordon | ref = CITEREFSmith1991 | edition = 2nd }}\n* {{Cite book | author = Swain, Geoff | title = Trotsky | publisher = [[Pearson Education]] | year = 2006  | isbn = 978-0582771901 | ref = CITEREFSwain2006 }}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=van Ree|first=Erik|title=The Political Thought of Joseph Stalin: A Study in Twentieth Century Revolutionary Patriotism|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tLZy9dhBsPgC|year=2003|publisher=[[Routledge]]|isbn=978-1-135-78604-5}}\n* {{cite book | author = Volkogonov, Dmitri | title = Autopsy for an Empire : The Seven Leaders Who Built the Soviet Regime | year = 1999 | publisher = Free Press | isbn = 978-0684834207 | ref = CITEREFVolkogonov1999 | url = https://archive.org/details/autopsyforempire00volk }}\n* {{ cite book | author = Williams, Simons | title = The Party Statutes of the Communist World | year = 1984 | isbn = 978-9024729753 | publisher = [[BRILL Publishers]] | ref = CITEREFSimons1984 }}\n* {{ cite book | author = Zimmerman, William | title = The Twenty-fifth Congress of the CPSU: Assessment and Context | year = 1977 | isbn = 978-0817968434 | publisher = [[Stanford University]]. [[Hoover Press]] | editor = Dallin, Alexander | ref = CITEREFZimmerman1977 }}\n\n{{Refend}}\n{{Soviet Union topics}}\n{{Marxism\u2013Leninism}}\n\n[[Category:Ideology of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union| ]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:State ideologies|Communist Party of the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:3ed0:9990:39b4:3a33:6958:6e92", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMarxism\u2013Leninism)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideology_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union"}
{"title_page": "Margarites helicinus", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Margarites helicinus\n| image = Margarites helicinus 002.jpg\n| image_caption =  Drawing with an apertural view of a shell of ''Margarites helicinus''\n| authority = (Phipps, 1774)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\"/><ref>[http://mollus.oxfordjournals.org/content/43/supp3/41.extract Journal of Molluscan Studies 43:3, pp. 41\u201345]</ref>\n| synonyms =\n* ''Clio helicinus'' <small>Phipps, 1774</small>\n* ''Eumargarita helicinus'' <small>Phipps, 1774</small> \n* ''Eumargarites helicinus'' <small>(Phipps, 1774)</small>\n* ''Helix margarita'' <small>Montagu, 1808</small>\n* ''Margarita arctica'' <small>Leach, 1819</small>\n* ''Margarita campanulata'' <small>Packard, 1867</small>\n* ''Margarita communis'' <small>W. Thompson, 1844</small> \n* ''Margarita depressior'' <small>Middendorff, 1849</small> \n* ''Margarita helicina'' <small>(Phipps, 1774)</small>\n* ''Margarita helicoides'' <small>Sowerby I, 1838</small> \n* ''Margarita major'' <small>Middendorff, 1848</small> \n* ''Margarita normalis'' <small>Middendorff, 1849</small> \n* ''Margarita typica'' <small>Middendorff, 1849</small> \n* ''Margarita vulgaris'' <small>Sowerby I, 1838</small> \n* ''Margarites albolineatus'' <small>Smith, E.A., 1899</small>\n* ''Margarites beringensis'' <small>(E. A. Smith, 1899)</small>\n* ''Margarites diaphanus'' <small>Gray, 1847</small>\n* ''Margarites elevatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small> \n* ''Margarites excavatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small> \n* ''Paludina inflatus'' <small>Totten, 1834</small> \n* ''Trochus fasciatus'' <small>Jeffreys, 1865</small> \n* ''Trochus helicinus'' <small>Fabricius, 1780</small> \n* ''Trochus neritoideus'' <small>Gmelin, 1791</small> \n* ''Turbo helicinus'' <small>Phipps, 1774</small> (original combination)\n* ''Turbo inflatus'' <small>Totten, 1834</small> \n* ''Turbo margarita'' <small>Montagu, 1808</small> \n* ''Valvatella albolineata'' <small>E. A. Smith, 1899</small> \n* ''Valvatella beringensis'' <small>E. A. Smith, 1899</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Margarites helicinus''''', [[common name]] the '''helicina margarite''' or '''spiral margarite''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Margaritidae]].<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|141821|''Margarites helicinus'' (Phipps, 1774)||6 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Margarites helicinus'' has been established by Phipps in 1774 and not by Fabricus in 1780 as Winchworth (1932), Sneli (1970) (and others) mention.\n\nDall established in 1919 two varieties,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofuni561920unit Dall (1919) Descriptions of new species of Mollusca from the North Pacific Ocean; Proceedings of the U.S. National Museum, vol. 56 (1920) ]</ref> but both have become synonyms of ''Margarites helicinus''.\n* ''Margarites helicinus'' var. ''elevatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small>\n* ''Margarites helicinus'' var. ''excavatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 3. mm and 11&nbsp;mm.\nThe umbilicate, thin shell has a depressed-conoidal shape. It is flesh-colored, with paler at periphery and below the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]], fading into corneous around the [[Umbilicus (mollusc)|umbilicus]]. The surface is very bright, shining, polished, and smooth except for fine subobsolete concentric lines around the [[Umbilicus (mollusc)|umbilicus]]. The [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]] is conoidal. The [[Apex (mollusc)|apex]] is minute but obtuse. The suture is impressed. The shell contains about 5 convex [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s, the last very rapidly widening, somewhat descending toward the [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]]. The rounded aperture is oblique, angular above, nacreous inside. The pearly iridescence is often visible through the shell. The narrow [[Umbilicus (mollusc)|umbilicus]] is profound. Its opening is regularly curved, not separated from the base by a carina.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualofconcholo111tryo Tryon (1889), Manual of Conchology XI, Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs near the seashore in circum-arctic waters, in the North Atlantic, in European waters; from the [[Bering Strait]] to [[California]], USA; in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]].\n\n==Spawning and development==\n[[Spawning]] takes place during the spring in the [[San Juan Islands]], WA, USA.  Prior to spawning two to four snails move close together, one of these is a female and all others are male.  A female release eggs only when in close proximity to a male.  Eggs are released in a mucus strand 2\u20133 eggs wide.  Eggs are orange to pinkish red, 180\u2013200&nbsp;\u00b5m in diameter, and each egg is covered by a gelatinous layer 10\u201330&nbsp;\u00b5m thick.  Sperm release is not visible during spawning but must occur since eggs in newly produced egg masses are fertilized.  The female uses the leading edge of her foot to form the mucus strand into a globular egg mass 0.5\u20131.5&nbsp;cm in diameter.  Each egg masses contains 90\u20131000 eggs, and egg masses are anchored to algal surfaces at both ends of the egg mass.<ref name=Strathmann>{{citation |author=Strathmann, M.F. |year=1987 |title=Reproduction and development of marine invertebrates of the northern Pacific coast |publisher=University of Washington Press, 670p}}</ref><ref name=Holyoak>{{citation |author=Holyoak, A.R. |year=1988 |title=Spawning, egg mass formation, and larval development of the trochid gastropod ''Margarites helicinus'' |publisher=The Veliger 31: 111\u2013113}}</ref>\n\nAll embryonic and larval development takes place in the egg mass and young emerge as juvenile snails.<ref name=Strathmann /><ref name=Holyoak /> Development proceeds as eggs undergo [[spiral cleavage]].  Timing of development at 7\u20139&nbsp;\u00b0C proceeds as embryos reached the [[gastrula]] stage 1.3 days after fertilization, the [[trochophore]] stage 2.1 days after fertilization, the [[veliger]] stage 3.3 days after fertilization, [[Torsion (gastropod)|torsion]] between 4.5\u20135 days after fertilization, [[metamorphosis]] at 10.5 days, and hatched and crawled out of the egg mass as a juvenile snail at 12.1 days.<ref name=Holyoak />\n\nShells of newly emergent juvenile snails are 270\u2013300&nbsp;\u00b5m long.<ref name=Strathmann /><ref name=Holyoak />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Phipps, C. J. 1774. ''A Voyage towards the North Pole''.  viii + 253 pp., 12 pls. J. Nourse: London. \n* Gmelin, J. F. 1791. ''Systema naturae per regna tria naturae. Editio decima tertia''. Systema Naturae, 13th ed., vol. 1(6): 3021\u20133910. Lipsiae. \n* Montagu, G. 1808. ''Supplement to Testacea Britannica.''  [iii] + v + 184 pp., 30 pls. S. Woolmer: Exeter.\n* Leach, W. E. 1819. ''A list of invertebrate animals, discovered by his majesty's ship Isabella, in a voyage to the Arctic regions.'' A Voyage of Discovery. Appendix II, Zoological Memoranda lxi\u2013lxiv John Murray: London.\n* Totten, J. G. 1834. ''Description of some new shells, belonging to the coast of New England.'' American Journal of Science and Arts 26: 366\u2013369, 1 pl. \n* Sowerby, G. B., I. 1838. ''A descriptive catalogue of the species of Leach's genus Margarita''. Malacological and Conchological Magazine 1: 23\u201327.\n* Thompson, W. 1844. ''Report on the fauna of Ireland: Div. Invertebrata''. Report of the Thirteenth meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science 245\u2013291.\n* Middendorff, A. T. von. 1848. ''Vorl\u00e4ufige Anzeige einiger neuer Konchylien aus den Geschlectern: Littorina, Tritonium, Bullia, Natica und Margarita''. Bulletin de la Classe Physico-Math\u00e9matique de l'Acad\u00e9mie Imp\u00e9riale des Sciences de Saint-P\u00e9tersbourg 7: col. 241\u2013245\n* Middendorff, A. T. von. 1849. ''Beitr\u00e4ge zu einer Malacozoologia Rossica. II. Aufz\u00e4hlung und Beschreibung der zur Meeresfauna Russlands geh\u00f6rigen einschaler.'' M\u00e9moires de l'Acad\u00e9mie Imp\u00e9riale des Sciences de Saint-P\u00e9tersbourg, Sciences Naturelles (6)6: 329\u2013516, pls. 1\u201311. \n* Jeffreys, J. G. 1865. ''British conchology''. British Conchology 3: [ii] + 393 pp., frontispiece, 8 pls. John Van Voorst: London\n* Leche, W. 1878. ''\u00d6fversigt \u00f6fver de af Svenska Expeditionerna till Novaja Semlja och Jenissej 1875 och 1876 Insamlade: Hafs-Mollusker''. Kongliga Svenska Vetenskaps-Akademiens Handlingar (2)16(2): 1\u201386, pls. 1\u20132\n* Smith, E. A. 1899. ''On some Mollusca from Bering Sea, with descriptions of two new species of Trochidae''. Proceedings of the Malacological Society of London 3: 205\u2013207\n* Dall, W. H. 1919. ''Descriptions of new species of Mollusca from the North Pacific Ocean in the collection of the United States National Museum''. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 56(2295): 293\u2013371\n* Backeljau, T. (1986). ''Lijst van de recente mariene mollusken van Belgi\u00eb [List of the recent marine molluscs of Belgium]''. Koninklijk Belgisch Instituut voor Natuurwetenschappen: Brussels, Belgium. 106 pp.\n* Turgeon, D.D., et al. 1998. ''Common and scientific names of aquatic invertebrates of the United States and Canada''. American Fisheries Society Special Publication 26 page(s): 60\n* Gofas, S.; Le Renard, J.; Bouchet, P. (2001). Mollusca, in: Costello, M.J. et al. (Ed.) (2001). ''European register of marine species: a check-list of the marine species in Europe and a bibliography of guides to their identification.'' Collection Patrimoines Naturels, 50: pp.&nbsp;180\u2013213 \n* Kantor Yu.I. & Sysoev A.V. (2006) ''Marine and brackish water Gastropoda of Russia and adjacent countries: an illustrated catalogue''. Moscow: KMK Scientific Press. 372 pp. + 140 pls. page(s): 34\n* Gulbin V.V. & Chaban E.M. (2012) ''Annotated list of shell-bearing gastropods of Commander Islands. Part I.'' The Bulletin of the Russian Far East Malacological Society 15\u201316: 5\u201330.\n* Dyntaxa (2013) ''Swedish Taxonomic Database''.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=9|id=5529|title=''Margarites helicinus helicinus''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n{{Commons category|Margarites helicinus}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3176554}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Margarites Helicinus}}\n[[Category:Margarites|helicinus]]\n[[Category:Molluscs described in 1774]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| taxon = Margarites helicinus\n| image = Margarites helicinus 002.jpg\n| image_caption =  Drawing with an apertural view of a shell of ''Margarites helicinus''\n| authority = (Phipps, 1774)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\"/><ref>[http://mollus.oxfordjournals.org/content/43/supp3/41.extract Journal of Molluscan Studies 43:3, pp. 41-45]</ref>\n| synonyms =\n* ''Clio helicinus'' <small>Phipps, 1774</small>\n* ''Eumargarita helicinus'' <small>Phipps, 1774</small> \n* ''Eumargarites helicinus'' <small>(Phipps, 1774)</small>\n* ''Helix margarita'' <small>Montagu, 1808</small>\n* ''Margarita arctica'' <small>Leach, 1819</small>\n* ''Margarita campanulata'' <small>Packard, 1867</small>\n* ''Margarita communis'' <small>W. Thompson, 1844</small> \n* ''Margarita depressior'' <small>Middendorff, 1849</small> \n* ''Margarita helicina'' <small>(Phipps, 1774)</small>\n* ''Margarita helicoides'' <small>Sowerby I, 1838</small> \n* ''Margarita major'' <small>Middendorff, 1848</small> \n* ''Margarita normalis'' <small>Middendorff, 1849</small> \n* ''Margarita typica'' <small>Middendorff, 1849</small> \n* ''Margarita vulgaris'' <small>Sowerby I, 1838</small> \n* ''Margarites albolineatus'' <small>Smith, E.A., 1899</small>\n* ''Margarites beringensis'' <small>(E. A. Smith, 1899)</small>\n* ''Margarites diaphanus'' <small>Gray, 1847</small>\n* ''Margarites elevatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small> \n* ''Margarites excavatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small> \n* ''Paludina inflatus'' <small>Totten, 1834</small> \n* ''Trochus fasciatus'' <small>Jeffreys, 1865</small> \n* ''Trochus helicinus'' <small>Fabricius, 1780</small> \n* ''Trochus neritoideus'' <small>Gmelin, 1791</small> \n* ''Turbo helicinus'' <small>Phipps, 1774</small> (original combination)\n* ''Turbo inflatus'' <small>Totten, 1834</small> \n* ''Turbo margarita'' <small>Montagu, 1808</small> \n* ''Valvatella albolineata'' <small>E. A. Smith, 1899</small> \n* ''Valvatella beringensis'' <small>E. A. Smith, 1899</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Margarites helicinus''''', [[common name]] the '''helicina margarite''' or '''spiral margarite''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Margaritidae]].<ref name=\"WoRMS\">{{WRMS species|141821|''Margarites helicinus'' (Phipps, 1774)||6 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Margarites helicinus'' has been established by Phipps in 1774 and not by Fabricus in 1780 as Winchworth (1932), Sneli (1970) (and others) mention.\n\nDall established in 1919 two varieties,<ref>[https://archive.org/details/proceedingsofuni561920unit Dall (1919) Descriptions of new species of Mollusca from the North Pacific Ocean; Proceedings of the U.S. National Museum, vol. 56 (1920) ]</ref> but both have become synonyms of ''Margarites helicinus''.\n* ''Margarites helicinus'' var. ''elevatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small>\n* ''Margarites helicinus'' var. ''excavatus'' <small>Dall, 1919</small>\n\n==Description==\nThe size of the shell varies between 3. mm and 11&nbsp;mm.\nThe umbilicate, thin shell has a depressed-conoidal shape. It is flesh-colored, with paler at periphery and below the [[Suture (anatomy)|suture]], fading into corneous around the [[Umbilicus (mollusc)|umbilicus]]. The surface is very bright, shining, polished, and smooth except for fine subobsolete concentric lines around the [[Umbilicus (mollusc)|umbilicus]]. The [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]] is conoidal. The [[Apex (mollusc)|apex]] is minute but obtuse. The suture is impressed. The shell contains about 5 convex [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s, the last very rapidly widening, somewhat descending toward the [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]]. The rounded aperture is oblique, angular above, nacreous inside. The pearly iridescence is often visible through the shell. The narrow [[Umbilicus (mollusc)|umbilicus]] is profound. Its opening is regularly curved, not separated from the base by a carina.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/manualofconcholo111tryo Tryon (1889), Manual of Conchology XI, Academy of Natural Sciences, Philadelphia]</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs near the seashore in circum-arctic waters, in the North Atlantic, in European waters; from the [[Bering Strait]] to [[California]], USA; in the [[Sea of Okhotsk]].\n\n==Spawning and development==\n[[Spawning]] takes place during the spring in the [[San Juan Islands]], WA, USA.  Prior to spawning two to four snails move close together, one of these is a female and all others are male.  A female release eggs only when in close proximity to a male.  Eggs are released in a mucus strand 2-3 eggs wide.  Eggs are orange to pinkish red, 180-200&nbsp;\u00b5m in diameter, and each egg is covered by a gelatinous layer 10-30&nbsp;\u00b5m thick.  Sperm release is not visible during spawning but must occur since eggs in newly produced egg masses are fertilized.  The female uses the leading edge of her foot to form the mucus strand into a globular egg mass 0.5-1.5&nbsp;cm in diameter.  Each egg masses contains 90-1000 eggs, and egg masses are anchored to algal surfaces at both ends of the egg mass.<ref name=Strathmann>{{citation |author=Strathmann, M.F. |year=1987 |title=Reproduction and development of marine invertebrates of the northern Pacific coast |publisher=University of Washington Press, 670p}}</ref><ref name=Holyoak>{{citation |author=Holyoak, A.R. |year=1988 |title=Spawning, egg mass formation, and larval development of the trochid gastropod ''Margarites helicinus'' |publisher=The Veliger 31: 111-113}}</ref>\n\nAll embryonic and larval development takes place in the egg mass and young emerge as juvenile snails.<ref name=Strathmann /><ref name=Holyoak /> Development proceeds as eggs undergo [[spiral cleavage]].  Timing of development at 7-9&nbsp;\u00b0C proceeds as embryos reached the [[gastrula]] stage 1.3 days after fertilization, the [[trochophore]] stage 2.1 days after fertilization, the [[veliger]] stage 3.3 days after fertilization, [[Torsion (gastropod)|torsion]] between 4.5\u20135 days after fertilization, [[metamorphosis]] at 10.5 days, and hatched and crawled out of the egg mass as a juvenile snail at 12.1 days.<ref name=Holyoak />\n\nShells of newly emergent juvenile snails are 270-300&nbsp;\u00b5m long.<ref name=Strathmann /><ref name=Holyoak />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Phipps, C. J. 1774. ''A Voyage towards the North Pole''.  viii + 253 pp., 12 pls. J. Nourse: London. \n* Gmelin, J. F. 1791. ''Systema naturae per regna tria naturae. Editio decima tertia''. Systema Naturae, 13th ed., vol. 1(6): 3021\u20133910. Lipsiae. \n* Montagu, G. 1808. ''Supplement to Testacea Britannica.''  [iii] + v + 184 pp., 30 pls. S. Woolmer: Exeter.\n* Leach, W. E. 1819. ''A list of invertebrate animals, discovered by his majesty's ship Isabella, in a voyage to the Arctic regions.'' A Voyage of Discovery. Appendix II, Zoological Memoranda lxi-lxiv John Murray: London.\n* Totten, J. G. 1834. ''Description of some new shells, belonging to the coast of New England.'' American Journal of Science and Arts 26: 366\u2013369, 1 pl. \n* Sowerby, G. B., I. 1838. ''A descriptive catalogue of the species of Leach's genus Margarita''. Malacological and Conchological Magazine 1: 23\u201327.\n* Thompson, W. 1844. ''Report on the fauna of Ireland: Div. Invertebrata''. Report of the Thirteenth meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science 245\u2013291.\n* Middendorff, A. T. von. 1848. ''Vorl\u00e4ufige Anzeige einiger neuer Konchylien aus den Geschlectern: Littorina, Tritonium, Bullia, Natica und Margarita''. Bulletin de la Classe Physico-Math\u00e9matique de l'Acad\u00e9mie Imp\u00e9riale des Sciences de Saint-P\u00e9tersbourg 7: col. 241-245\n* Middendorff, A. T. von. 1849. ''Beitr\u00e4ge zu einer Malacozoologia Rossica. II. Aufz\u00e4hlung und Beschreibung der zur Meeresfauna Russlands geh\u00f6rigen einschaler.'' M\u00e9moires de l'Acad\u00e9mie Imp\u00e9riale des Sciences de Saint-P\u00e9tersbourg, Sciences Naturelles (6)6: 329\u2013516, pls. 1-11. \n* Jeffreys, J. G. 1865. ''British conchology''. British Conchology 3: [ii] + 393 pp., frontispiece, 8 pls. John Van Voorst: London\n* Leche, W. 1878. ''\u00d6fversigt \u00f6fver de af Svenska Expeditionerna till Novaja Semlja och Jenissej 1875 och 1876 Insamlade: Hafs-Mollusker''. Kongliga Svenska Vetenskaps-Akademiens Handlingar (2)16(2): 1-86, pls. 1-2\n* Smith, E. A. 1899. ''On some Mollusca from Bering Sea, with descriptions of two new species of Trochidae''. Proceedings of the Malacological Society of London 3: 205-207\n* Dall, W. H. 1919. ''Descriptions of new species of Mollusca from the North Pacific Ocean in the collection of the United States National Museum''. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 56(2295): 293-371\n* Backeljau, T. (1986). ''Lijst van de recente mariene mollusken van Belgi\u00eb [List of the recent marine molluscs of Belgium]''. Koninklijk Belgisch Instituut voor Natuurwetenschappen: Brussels, Belgium. 106 pp.\n* Turgeon, D.D., et al. 1998. ''Common and scientific names of aquatic invertebrates of the United States and Canada''. American Fisheries Society Special Publication 26 page(s): 60\n* Gofas, S.; Le Renard, J.; Bouchet, P. (2001). Mollusca, in: Costello, M.J. et al. (Ed.) (2001). ''European register of marine species: a check-list of the marine species in Europe and a bibliography of guides to their identification.'' Collection Patrimoines Naturels, 50: pp.&nbsp;180\u2013213 \n* Kantor Yu.I. & Sysoev A.V. (2006) ''Marine and brackish water Gastropoda of Russia and adjacent countries: an illustrated catalogue''. Moscow: KMK Scientific Press. 372 pp. + 140 pls. page(s): 34\n* Gulbin V.V. & Chaban E.M. (2012) ''Annotated list of shell-bearing gastropods of Commander Islands. Part I.'' The Bulletin of the Russian Far East Malacological Society 15-16: 5\u201330.\n* Dyntaxa (2013) ''Swedish Taxonomic Database''.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=9|id=5529|title=''Margarites helicinus helicinus''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n{{Commons category|Margarites helicinus}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3176554}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Margarites Helicinus}}\n[[Category:Margarites|helicinus]]\n[[Category:Molluscs described in 1774]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margarites_helicinus"}
{"title_page": "Martin Solveig discography", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist discography\n| Artist       = [[Martin Solveig]]\n| Logo         =\n| Image        = Martin_Solveig_Pukkelpop_2009.jpg\n| Caption      = Solveig at [[Pukkelpop]] music festival\n| Studio       = 5\n| Compilation  = 1\n| Live         =\n| Video        =\n| Music videos =\n| Singles      = 26\n}}\n\nThe discography of [[Martin Solveig]], a French DJ and record producer, consists of four [[studio album]]s, one [[compilation album]] and twenty-six [[Single (music)|singles]] (including one as a featured artist).\n\nHis debut studio album, ''Sur la terre'', was released in June 2002. The album includes the singles \"[[Madan (song)|Madan]]\", \"[[Rocking Music]]\" and \"[[I'm a Good Man]]\".\n\nHis second studio album, ''Hedonist'', was released in September 2005, the album peaked at number 43 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]. The album includes the singles \"[[Everybody (Martin Solveig song)|Everybody]]\", \"[[Jealousy (Martin Solveig song)|Jealousy]]\", \"Something Better\" and \"[[Rejection (song)|Rejection]]\".\n\nHis third studio album, ''[[C'est la Vie (Martin Solveig album)|C'est la Vie]]'', was released in October 2008, the album peaked at number 16 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]].  \"[[C'est la Vie (Martin Solveig song)|C'est la Vie]]\" was released as the lead single from the album on 21 January 2008. \"[[I Want You (Martin Solveig song)|I Want You]]\" was released as the second single from the album on 15 September 2008. \"[[One 2.3 Four]]\" was released as the third single from the album on 22 December 2008. \"[[Boys & Girls (Martin Solveig song)|Boys & Girls]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album on 28 September 2009.\n\nHis fourth studio album, ''[[Smash (Martin Solveig album)|Smash]]'', was released in June 2011, peaking at number 18 on the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|French Albums Chart]]. On 6 September 2010 he released the single \"[[Hello (Martin Solveig song)|Hello]]\" with [[Dragonette]] as the lead single from the album. It is Solveig's most successful single to date, peaking at number one in [[Austria]], [[Belgium]] ([[Flanders]]), [[Czech Republic]] and the [[Netherlands]], while charting within the top 10 in ten other countries. The song also peaked at number 13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. \"[[Ready 2 Go]]\" was released as the second single from the album on 28 March 2011. On 24 October 2011 \"[[Big in Japan (Martin Solveig song)|Big in Japan]]\" was released as the third single from the album. On 2 April 2012 \"[[The Night Out]]\" was released as the fourth single from the album.\n\n==Albums==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11.5em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18.5em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br/><ref name=\"FRA\">{{cite web|url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Martin+Solveig|title=Discographie Martin Solveig|publisher=French Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL (Fl)]]<br/><ref name=\"FL\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Martin+Solveig|title=Discografie Martin Solveig|publisher=Belgium (Flanders) Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL (Wa)]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br/><ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/|title=Discographie Martin Solveig|format=enter \"Martin Solveig\" into the \"Suchen\" box|publisher=German Charts Portal. Hung Medien}}</